         <h1>Bruno Zevi, Architecture Critic With Populist Flair, Dies at 81 </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Bruno Zevi , editor of the Italian magazine L'Architettura and one of Europe 's most prominent architecture critics for five decades , died on Sunday at his home in Rome . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 81 . <br><blue>3</blue>Trained as an architect , Mr. Zevi was strongly influenced by Frank Lloyd Wright 's concept of organic architecture . <br><blue>4</blue>He designed a few structures , like the Italian pavilion at the 1967 World 's Fair in Montreal , and championed the commission of others , including Stazione Termini , Rome 's railway terminal . <br><blue>5</blue>But Mr. Zevi was best known as a writer . <br><blue>6</blue>His most influential books were '' Toward an Organic Architecture , '' published in 1945 , and '' Architecture as Space : How to Look at Architecture , '' first published in English in 1957 . <br><blue>7</blue>Building on Wright 's belief that the essence of architecture resides in voids rather than the solid forms that enclose them , the book reinterprets great buildings of the past in light of this modern idea . <br><blue>8</blue>Mr. Zevi did not pretend to be a neutral observer . <br><blue>9</blue>He dedicated '' Architecture as Space '' to '' all my friends in the organic architecture movement . '' <br><blue>10</blue>In a 1974 edition of the book , he took critical aim at other architects and writers . <br><blue>11</blue>With its acerbic and sometimes appreciative comments on Mr. Zevi 's contemporaries , the book remains a valuable guide to architectural thought in the postwar decades . <br><blue>12</blue>In the 1960 's and 70 's Mr. Zevi found himself cast in a factional split that still affects Italian architecture . <br><blue>13</blue>A humanist in the ancient tradition that dates from the Renaissance , he was rejected by a new guard led by Manfredo Tafuri . <br><blue>14</blue>Mr. Tafuri , who died in 1994 , was a Marxist historian and theorist who taught at the Istituto Universitario di Architettura in Venice . <br><blue>15</blue>His writings , particularly '' Theories and History of Architecture , '' helped transform the Venetian school into one of the world 's leading architecture academies . <br><blue>16</blue>They also provided the intellectual inspiration for the theory and history programs that have since proliferated in schools around the world . <br><blue>17</blue>Mr. Zevi , meanwhile , took on a more populist role as a public intellectual whose columns for the weekly news magazine L'Espresso attracted a broad readership . <br><blue>18</blue>His columns varied in length but were invariably outspoken . <br><blue>19</blue>He declined to subject buildings to rigorous ideological scrutiny . <br><blue>20</blue>Mr. Tafuri captured minds while Mr. Zevi won hearts . <br><hr><br><blue>1(3)</blue>: <m_str>the book</m_str> (10_6) 	<m_str>the book</m_str> (11_14) 	<m_str>the book</m_str> (7_23) 	<br><blue>2(1)</blue>: <m_str>L'Espresso</m_str> (17_23) 	<br><blue>3(18)</blue>: <m_str>His</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (19_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Zevi 's</m_str> (11_9) 	<m_str>Mr. Zevi</m_str> (8_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Zevi</m_str> (12_8) 	<m_str>himself</m_str> (12_11) 	<m_str>Mr. Zevi</m_str> (5_2) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Zevi</m_str> (20_6) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Zevi</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (6_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (13_13) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_27) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (10_9) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (18_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Zevi</m_str> (3_6) 	<br><blue>4(4)</blue>: <m_str>Architecture</m_str> (6_27) 	<m_str>architecture</m_str> (7_10) 	<m_str>Architecture</m_str> (6_19) 	<m_str>Architecture</m_str> (15_10) 	<br><blue>5(2)</blue>: <m_str>Rome 's</m_str> (4_31) 	<m_str>Rome</m_str> (1_30) 	<br><blue>6(2)</blue>: <m_str>the world 's</m_str> (15_21) 	<m_str>the world</m_str> (16_20) 	<br><blue>7(2)</blue>: <m_str>voids</m_str> (7_13) 	<m_str>them</m_str> (7_21) 	<br><blue>8(3)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Tafuri , who died in 1994</m_str> (14_1) 	<m_str>Manfredo Tafuri</m_str> (13_22) 	<m_str>Mr. Tafuri</m_str> (20_1) 	<br><blue>9(2)</blue>: <m_str>Frank Lloyd Wright 's</m_str> (3_12) 	<m_str>Wright 's</m_str> (7_3) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br>         </p>
